@Phoebe H 
Wow I really liked how deeply you thought into the information on the graph, especially your comment on high contact indoor buildings having closed circulation that causes more germs to be spread indoors than outdoors. While germs are spread more easily inside these locations, I don’t think it’ll cause a huge surge in new cases. People are still weary about going inside indoor buildings, so it might take a few weeks for people to even start feeling comfortable going back to restaurants and malls. I definitely have seen a lot of people in outdoor locations like parks and beaches though! 

To answer your question, I think that air travel would belong in the top right corner close to beauty salons and nail salons since people are trapped in an airplane for hours on end together. There’s a much higher risk of catching COVID-19 on an 18 hour long flight than a one hour meal inside a restaurant. And yes, I think that the amount of contact at places depends on the weather and season. No one’s going to want to go to the park or beach in 20 degree weather just like no one’s going to want to miss going outside on a sunny day. I also love your title. Even though wearing a mask nowadays is a sign of courtesy, they don’t guarantee safety.

